# Strict TDD Definition

Follow this sequence exactly for all feature and bug-fix work:

1. Define expected behavior and test scope.
2. Write tests first.
3. Run tests for a red phase.
   - If tests do not compile, add minimal stubs only to make tests compile and run.
   - Re-run until tests execute and fail for the intended reason (no false positives).
4. Green phase: implement behavior to the best of ability.
5. Run tests and verify green.
6. Refactor for clarity/maintainability without changing behavior.
7. Run tests again and verify green after refactor.

## Required Evidence

- Show/record at least one failing test run in red phase.
- Show/record a passing run after green implementation.
- Show/record a passing run after refactor.

## Guardrails

- Do not skip red phase.
- Do not treat compile-only failure as complete red phase when runtime-failing tests are possible.
- Do not merge or close work with failing tests.
